[[File:Honor bilt modern homes. (1921) (14761021821).jpg|thumb|320px|right|'''Cottage windows''' are visible in this view of a [[bungalow]]-style house dating to 1921.]]
A '''cottage window''' is a [[double-hung window]] — i.e., a window with two sashes sliding up and down, hung with one atop the other in the same frame — in which the upper sash is smaller (shorter) than the lower one. The upper sash often contains smaller lights divided by [[Muntin|muntins]] (often known as a "divided light pattern" or "grille"), although in some cases both sashes may be divided.
Cottage windows are especially characteristic of [[bungalow]] or [[American Craftsman|Craftsman]]-style houses. Also called a "front window".
