'''Maria(no) Pardo de Figueroa''' of Medina (18 November 1828 – 11 December 1918),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://catalogue.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb16710454f|title=Notice d'autorité personne: Thebussem, Doctor (1828-1918)|work=[[Bibliothèque nationale de France]]|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref> who used the nom-de-plume Dr. Thebussem (or Thebussen), was a Spanish nobleman and [[philatelist]] who was one of the "Fathers of Philately" entered on the [[Roll of Distinguished Philatelists]] in 1921. He was elected an Ordinary Member of ''The Philatelic Society, London'', now the [[Royal Philatelic Society London]], in 1870 and an Honorary Member of that Society in 1875, and as such he was one of the first members of the Society.<ref>"The Royal Philatelic Society, London. 1869 - April 10th - 1929." by [[Percy de Worms]] in ''[[The London Philatelist]]'', Vol. XXXVIII, No. 447, March 1929, pp. 52-56.</ref> Election as an honorary member probably related to the rule that once existed that full members should be resident in London.
According to [[Gibbons Stamp Monthly|Gibbons Stamp Weekly]], de Figueroa was given the title of "Honorary Postman of Spain and her Possessions" for postal reforms in that country and the privilege of free postage for his services to science.<ref>"Philatelic peculiarities" by W. Ward in ''Gibbons Stamp Weekly'', November 1908, p. 311.</ref>
The pen name "Thebussem" was created from an anagram of "embustes" (Spanish for "lies" or "[[tall tales]]"), with an H and an S added to [[Germanization|Germanize]] it.<ref name="Díaz Pérez">{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2010/01/20/andalucia/1263980782.html|title=Doctor Thebussem, el rey de los apócrifos|last=Díaz Pérez|first=Eva|date=20 January 2010|work=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>
The well-known Spanish writer [[Dionisio Pérez Gutiérrez]] chose to go by the pseudonym "Post-Thebussem" as a show of support for de Figueroa.<ref name="Anderson2012">{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Lara|date=Winter 2012|title=Spanish Culinary Autochtony & Culinary Modernity: Maria Mestayer de Echagüe’s ''La cocina completa'' & ''Platos escogidos de la cocina vasca''|journal=[[Cincinnati Romance Review]]|volume=33|pages=98–113|url=http://www.cromrev.com/volumes/vol33/05-vol33-Anderson.pdf}}</ref>
==Publications== * ''Literatura philatélica en España. Apuntes para la redaccion de un catálogo''. 1876. * ''Fruslerías postales''. 1895. * ''Algo de philatelia''. 1899.
